these contrasts. Heart infarction is the predominant cause of death in Norway, 
with a mortality five times higher than in Japan and three times higher than in 
France. Both Norway and France have three times higher mortality rates for 
breast cancer than found in Japan, and the mortality rate for cervical cancer is 
twice as high in Norway as in the two other countries. Norwegian women show a 
mortality rate for lung cancer that is twice as high as that of their French 
sisters. Suicide among young Norwegians is a rapidly growing problem, and twice 
as common among Norwegian men aged 20-24 than among Japanese men of the same 
age. We challenge the health authorities and the specialists in the relevant 
fields to reflect again on their preventive strategies, in light of these 
contrasts.

